## Coding Standards — Enforce These In Every File

### General RTL Rules
- All RTL is synthesizable SystemVerilog (IEEE 1800-2017)
- Never use initial blocks in synthesizable RTL (only in testbenches)
- Never use #delays in synthesizable RTL
- Use always_ff for sequential logic, always_comb for combinational logic
- Never use always @ — always use always_ff or always_comb
- Use logic type exclusively — never use reg or wire
- All module ports must have explicit direction and type
- Every module must have a file header comment block (see template below)
- Reset is synchronous, active-low (rst_n) throughout the entire design
- Clock is always named clk
- Parameterize everything that could reasonably vary:
  - DATA_WIDTH, ADDR_WIDTH, ARRAY_SIZE, etc.
- Use localparam for constants internal to a module
- Use package files for shared typedefs and parameters

### Naming Conventions
- Module names: snake_case (e.g., pe_array, hazard_unit)
- Signal names: snake_case (e.g., rd_addr, wr_en)
- Parameters: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., DATA_WIDTH, ARRAY_SIZE)
- Constants/localparams: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Active-low signals: suffix _n (e.g., rst_n, valid_n)
- Registered signals: suffix _r (e.g., data_r, state_r)
- Next-state signals: suffix _next (e.g., state_next, count_next)
- Interface signals follow AXI naming convention exactly where applicable

### File Header Template (use on every file)
//=============================================================================
// Module: <module_name>
// Description: <one line description>
//
// Parameters:
//   <PARAM_NAME> - <description> (default: <value>)
//
// Ports:
//   <port_name> - <direction> - <description>
//
// Dependencies:
//   <list any submodules instantiated>
//
// Notes:
//   <any implementation notes, timing constraints, known limitations>
//=============================================================================

