## Phase 1: RISC-V RV32IM CPU

### Architecture Specification

Implement a classic 5-stage in-order pipeline:
  IF → ID → EX → MEM → WB

Pipeline registers between every stage:
  if_id_r, id_ex_r, ex_mem_r, mem_wb_r

Each pipeline register is a packed struct defined in a package file.

### Hazard Handling
- Full forwarding paths: EX/MEM → EX, MEM/WB → EX
- Load-use hazard: insert one bubble (stall IF and ID, flush EX)
- Control hazard: assume not-taken, flush on misprediction (2-cycle penalty)
- Forwarding unit is a separate module (forward_unit.sv)
- Hazard detection unit is a separate module (hazard_unit.sv)

### Instruction Set
Implement full RV32IM:
- RV32I base: all integer instructions including LUI, AUIPC, JAL, JALR,
  all branch types, all load types, all store types, all immediate arithmetic,
  all register arithmetic, FENCE (NOP), ECALL/EBREAK (NOP)
- M extension: MUL, MULH, MULHSU, MULHU, DIV, DIVU, REM, REMU
  (Use DSP48 primitives for multiply, iterative division is acceptable)

### Memory Interface
- Separate instruction memory and data memory (Harvard architecture)
- Both are synchronous BRAM with 1-cycle read latency
- Size: 64KB instruction memory, 64KB data memory (parameterizable)
- BRAM instantiation must use Xilinx BRAM primitives for synthesis
  (use behavioral model in simulation)

### Performance Target
- Achieve timing closure at ≥100MHz on Zynq-7020
- Target utilization: <20,000 LUTs, <10,000 FFs, <8 BRAMs

### Verification Requirements for CPU
- Directed assembly tests for every instruction in /sw/tests/
- Test back-to-back dependent instructions to verify forwarding
- Test load-use hazard explicitly
- Test branch taken and not-taken
- Test all multiply/divide corner cases (divide by zero, overflow)
- Simulate a complete bubble sort on 16 elements
- Show all test results pass in README with waveform screenshots

