## Phase 4: UVM Testbench

### Environment Structure
Follow standard UVM 1.2 class hierarchy:
  uvm_test → uvm_env → uvm_agent → (uvm_driver + uvm_monitor)
  uvm_env also contains: uvm_scoreboard, uvm_coverage_collector

### Sequence Item (accel_seq_item.sv)
class accel_seq_item extends uvm_sequence_item;
  rand logic [7:0] weights [ARRAY_SIZE][ARRAY_SIZE];
  rand logic [7:0] inputs  [ARRAY_SIZE][ARRAY_SIZE];
  logic [31:0]     expected [ARRAY_SIZE][ARRAY_SIZE]; // computed by post_randomize
  
  // Constraints
  constraint c_weight_range { foreach(weights[i,j]) weights[i][j] inside {[0:127]}; }
  constraint c_input_range  { foreach(inputs[i,j])  inputs[i][j]  inside {[0:127]}; }
  // Zero matrix test
  constraint c_zero_weights { weights.sum() with (int'(item)) == 0; }
  // Must enable/disable constraints in test

  function void post_randomize();
    // Compute expected output in pure SV for scoreboard reference
    foreach(expected[i,j]) begin
      expected[i][j] = 0;
      for(int k=0; k<ARRAY_SIZE; k++)
        expected[i][j] += weights[i][k] * inputs[k][j];
    end
  endfunction

### Functional Coverage (accel_coverage.sv)
covergroup accel_cg with function sample(accel_seq_item item);
  // Cover zero weight matrix
  cp_zero_weights: coverpoint (item.weights.sum() == 0) { bins zero = {1}; }
  // Cover max value inputs
  cp_max_input: coverpoint item.inputs[0][0] {
    bins low    = {[0:63]};
    bins high   = {[64:127]};
    bins max    = {127};
  }
  // Cover back-to-back transactions (cross coverage)
  cp_consecutive: coverpoint consecutive_txn_count {
    bins single = {1};
    bins burst  = {[2:5]};
    bins stress = {[6:$]};
  }
endgroup

Target: 90% coverage closure before declaring verification complete.

### Reference Model
The scoreboard must use an independent C++ reference model via DPI-C,
not a SystemVerilog reimplementation of the same algorithm.
Generate a simple C function:
  void matmul_ref(uint8_t *weights, uint8_t *inputs, 
                  uint32_t *outputs, int size);
Call it from the scoreboard to get expected values.
This is industry practice — the reference model must be algorithmically 
independent of the RTL.

